Last week, we trapped a stray dog thinking it was our neighborhood friend that we had been feeding for the last year or so. Since she was obviously still lactating, we released her the next day attached to a long leash to see if she would lead us to her puppies. And guess where she led us to? A slaughterhouse!! Momma ended up being a random loose dog that had ventured out from a dog meat farm tucked away in the mountains. Hiding in plain sight. Because all of them were barely fed (and if they were it was always food waste), some were forced to resort to cannibalism and others like Momma had to find scraps on the street to produce milk for her babies. We honestly canâ€™t take on this many dogs, but after seeing the horrific conditions they had endured, we knew we couldnâ€™t leave them behind, not even for another hour. We rescued 26 dogs that day, half of them puppies. RIP to the 2 dogs who died a death that was absolutely avoidable. Fly high, angels.

snippet.title: Your support for CatchDog Team saves lives
snippet.description:
Your support for Catchdog Team saves lives

We want to take this opportunity to thank our amazing supporters around the world.

Thanks to your PayPal donations, we have been able to save the lives of so many dogs.
Because of your critical support, these dogs can see another day to not only live but thrive. 

As you can see from our YouTube videos, this line of work is not easy. It is at times soul-crushing but too many dogs are suffering for us to falter. We will not stop until every last dog in Korea is saved from the dog meat industry. 

What is particularly horrific about this industry is the way dogs are treated and killed. They are kept in small cages and barely have room to stretch out their legs. Most are fed scraps and have limited access to water. And when they are dragged to their deaths, they are tortured in ways that even the darkest imaginations cannot fathom, and die a slow and painful death, often in front of their friends and family. 

Studies have proven that animal abusers are more likely to become serial killers. They start with small creatures that are unable to fight back. The number of cases that have skyrocketed in recent months and years is truly disturbing.

 As Mahatma Gandhi once said, â€œThe greatness of a nation and its moral progress can be judged by the way its animals are treated.â€ It is deeply shameful and preposterous how we treat other animals. 

We see this as a problem that transcends national borders and cultures, and are painfully aware that change cannot happen overnight. And our actions barely make a dent in the grand scheme of things. But little things can add up to make a big difference. 

It is with this belief that we march onward. Whether it be one stray dog or a dog meat farm with hundreds of dogs, we will not turn a blind eye to any being that is suffering or needs our help. Humans are at the top of the food chain. We have the power to dominate but we do not have the right to plunder and destroy. We should be guardians, not masters. 

Without your support, this would not have been possible. We canâ€™t thank you enough and hope that you will continue to open your hearts to animals in Korea.
